<DOC><DOCNO> AP891018-0028 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0203EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a BC-USQuakes     10-18 0303</FIRST><SECOND>BC-US Quakes,0319</SECOND><HEAD>List of Deadliest U.S. Quakes</HEAD><HEAD>With SF Quake</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Tuesday's earthquake in the San Francisco Bay area apparentlywas the second-deadliest in U.S. history. Here is a list of majorquakes as recorded by the U. S. Geological Survey:</TEXT><NOTE>SAN FRANCISCO, APRIL 18-19, 1906</NOTE><TEXT>   Rated at 8.3 on the Richter scale. Ruptured gas lines,overturned stoves and started fires that destroyed much of the cityand claimed hundreds of lives. Traditional estimates put the deathtoll at 500 to 700, but the city archivist recently establishedthat at least 2,500, and possibly 5,000 people were killed.</TEXT><NOTE>SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, OCT. 17, 1989</NOTE><TEXT>   Registered 6.9 on the Richter scale. Collapsed a mile-longstretch of double-deck highway, inflicted widespread damage tobuildings. Struck at evening rush hour. More than 200 people killedand 400 injured, according to early official reports.</TEXT><NOTE>PRINCE WILLIAM SOUND, ALASKA, MARCH 27, 1964</NOTE><TEXT>   Richter reading 8.4. The infamous Good Friday Earthquake. Therewere 131 deaths and extensive damage in Alaska.</TEXT><NOTE>MONA PASSAGE, PUERTO RICO, OCT. 11, 1918</NOTE><TEXT>   Rated at 7.5 on the Richter scale. Shook the Mona Passagebetween Puerto Rico and the island of Hispaniola. Some 116 peopledied, many in the giant wave generated by the quake.</TEXT><NOTE>LONG BEACH, CALIF., MARCH 10, 1933</NOTE><TEXT>   Rated at 6.2 on the Richter scale. Hit a heavily populated area.Many buildings collapsed, including schools, and 115 people werekilled.</TEXT><NOTE>SAN FERNANDO VALLEY, CALIF., FEB. 9, 1971</NOTE><TEXT>   Richter reading 6.4. Killed 65 people.</TEXT><NOTE>CHARLESTON, S.C., AUG. 31, 1886</NOTE><TEXT>   Rated at 6.6 on the Richter scale. Killed 60 people. Was felt asfar away as Boston, Milwaukee and Havana, Cuba.</TEXT><NOTE>HEBGEN LAKE, MONT., AUG. 17, 1959</NOTE><TEXT>   Richter reading 7.3. Was felt from Seattle to North Dakota toUtah. Extensive damage was reported and 28 people died.</TEXT></DOC>